---

# Neutral Palette

Neutral colours provide balance and improve readability.

Recommended neutrals include:

| Colour     | Typical Use                                  |
| ---------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| White      | Backgrounds, text and icons on dark surfaces |
| Black      | Text, icons and light backgrounds            |
| Dark Grey  | Primary application background               |
| Light Grey | Dividers, borders and secondary elements     |

Neutral colours should support the interface without competing with the primary brand colours.

---

# Colour Consistency

Official colours should remain visually consistent across all platforms.

Avoid unnecessary variation between:

* Websites
* Mobile applications
* Desktop software
* Documentation
* Presentations
* Printed material

Where colour profiles differ between digital and print media, use the closest possible match.

---

# Colour Usage

The LiVEiT® palette should be used with restraint.

Primary colours should guide attention rather than dominate the interface.

Good practice includes:

* Using colour to communicate structure.
* Maintaining strong contrast between foreground and background.
* Using neutral colours to provide visual balance.
* Applying accent colours consistently.

---

# Accessibility

Colour should never be the only method used to communicate information.

Interfaces should also use:

* Labels
* Icons
* Typography
* Layout
* Visual hierarchy

Text should maintain sufficient contrast against its background to support readability.

---

# Gradients

Gradients may be used where they are part of the official LiVEiT® design language.

They should remain subtle and should not reduce readability or recognition of the brand.

Custom gradients should not replace official brand colours.

---

# Transparency

Transparency effects, including glass-style interfaces, may be used where they support the overall user experience.

Effects should remain subtle and should never reduce accessibility or legibility.

---

# Colour Accuracy

Official brand colours should not be altered.

Avoid:

* Arbitrary hue changes
* Excessive saturation
* Unapproved tints
* Unapproved gradients
* Colour substitutions

Consistency strengthens recognition of the LiVEiT® brand.

---

# Future Expansion

Additional colours may be introduced for new products or services where appropriate.

New colours should complement the existing palette while preserving the recognisable identity of the LiVEiT® Framework.

---

# Registered Trademark

The LiVEiT® colour palette forms part of the overall visual identity of the framework.

While individual colours cannot themselves be protected, their consistent application contributes to the recognition of the LiVEiT® brand and should be used in accordance with this Branding Guide.
